Yes, your test class currently doesn&#39;t have any test methods. A test
method is a &quot;@Test public void&quot; (non-static), can be named as you
wish, and can throw any exception. For example:

public class TestX {
    @Test
    public void numbersAboveOneShouldGetDoubled() throws Exception {
        assertEquals(4, new X().met(2));
        assertEquals(6, new X().met(3));
        assertEquals(8, new X().met(4));
    }

    @Test
    public void numbersEqualOrBelowOneShouldYield666() throws Exception {
        assertEquals(666, new X().met(1));
        assertEquals(666, new X().met(0));
        assertEquals(666, new X().met(-4));
    }
}


On 10/22/06, t703093 &lt;t703093@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Both files are placed in a different directory then JUnit directory?
&gt; Is that a problem?

That&#39;s not a problem. Directories don&#39;t matter as long as all the
compiled .class files are in the class path while running JUnit.
Whether they&#39;re all in one directory tree, in two directory trees, in
one directory and three .jar files, doesn&#39;t matter.


